<bibRefCitation author="Michelangeli, FA" journalOrPublisher="Brittonia" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" pagination="82 - 88" publicationUrl="10.1007/s12228-013-9317-x" refId="B27" refString="Michelangeli, FA, 2014. Taxonomic notes on myrmecophilous Melastomataceae: a new species, two new synonyms, and an old species reconsidered. Brittonia 66: 82 - 88, DOI: 10.1007/s12228-013-9317-x" title="Taxonomic notes on myrmecophilous Melastomataceae: a new species, two new synonyms, and an old species reconsidered." url="10.1007/s12228-013-9317-x" volume="66" year="2014">Michelangeli 2014</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Michelangeli, FA" journalOrPublisher="Brittonia" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" pagination="170 - 173" publicationUrl="10.1007/s12228-013-9321-1" refId="B28" refString="Michelangeli, FA, Goldenberg, R, 2014. A new species of Graffenrieda (Melastomataceae) from the northern Amazon basin. Brittonia 66: 170 - 173, DOI: 10.1007/s12228-013-9321-1" title="A new species of Graffenrieda (Melastomataceae) from the northern Amazon basin." url="10.1007/s12228-013-9321-1" volume="66" year="2014">Michelangeli and Goldenberg 2014</bibRefCitation>
). All but one of these species have very restricted distributions, underscoring that because our knowledge of plant diversity in Amazonia is still based mostly on a 
<pageBreakToken pageId="4" pageNumber="35" start="start">few</pageBreakToken>
well sampled localities, we still have a long way to go before we have a complete knowledge of the biodiversity of this region.
</paragraph>
