<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" type="morphological comments">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Morphological comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Miconia papillosperma" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="papillosperma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Miconia papillosperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a very distinctive species that really does not closely resemble any other species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="tribe" tribe="Miconieae">Miconieae</taxonomicName>
known to us. Most of the specimens are in fruit and this is presumably why it remained undescribed until now. The elliptic-lanceolate to elliptic leaves with the only pair of secondaries very close to the margin resembles some species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Macairea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Macairea" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Macairea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
DC., an unrelated group with capsular fruits in the Marcetia clade (see Michelangeli 2013), but the leaf surface and indument are different. The shrubby habit and abundant red trichomes on the leaves and young stems resemble some species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="D.Don" authorityYear="1823" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Clidemia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Clidemia" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Clidemia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raddi" authorityYear="1820" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Leandra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Leandra" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Leandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Miconia" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Miconia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but no other species in these genera has the leaves of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Miconia papillosperma" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="papillosperma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Miconia papillosperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wurdack" authorityYear="1969" baseAuthorityName="Truana" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tococa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tococa rotundifolia" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rotundifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Tococa rotundifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Triana) Wurdack and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berg. ex Triana" authorityYear="1871" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tococa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tococa hirta" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hirta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Tococa hirta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="O’Berg">O'Berg</normalizedToken>
ex Triana also have similar reddish trichomes, but in both species at least one of the leaves of each pair has ant domatia and the venation pattern is quite different, with the secondaries running near halfway between the primary vein and the margin and not towards the margins of the lamina (
<bibRefCitation author="Michelangeli, FA" journalOrPublisher="Flora Neotropica Monographs" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 114" publicationUrl="http://www.jstor.org/stable/4393950" refId="B26" refString="Michelangeli, FA, 2005. A Monograph of Tococa Aublet (Melastomataceae). Flora Neotropica Monographs 98: 1 - 114, http://www.jstor.org/stable/4393950" title="A Monograph of Tococa Aublet (Melastomataceae)." url="http://www.jstor.org/stable/4393950" volume="98" year="2005">Michelangeli 2005</bibRefCitation>
). The flowers of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wurdack" authorityYear="1969" baseAuthorityName="Truana" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tococa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tococa rotundifolia" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rotundifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Tococa rotundifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with a winged hypanthium, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="can’t">can't</normalizedToken>
be confused with those of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Miconia papillosperma" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="papillosperma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Miconia papillosperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the broad conical hypanthium with a calyx with subulate outer teeth, the anthers with a dorsal connective blunt tooth, and the ovary with a corona of glandular trichomes at the apex, does resemble other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aublet" authorityYear="1775" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tococa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tococa" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Tococa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, most notably 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tococa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tococa ciliata" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Tococa ciliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Triana and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berg. ex Triana" authorityYear="1871" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tococa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tococa hirta" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hirta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Tococa hirta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Michelangeli, FA" journalOrPublisher="Flora Neotropica Monographs" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 114" publicationUrl="http://www.jstor.org/stable/4393950" refId="B26" refString="Michelangeli, FA, 2005. A Monograph of Tococa Aublet (Melastomataceae). Flora Neotropica Monographs 98: 1 - 114, http://www.jstor.org/stable/4393950" title="A Monograph of Tococa Aublet (Melastomataceae)." url="http://www.jstor.org/stable/4393950" volume="98" year="2005">Michelangeli 2005</bibRefCitation>
). However, the seeds of all species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aublet" authorityYear="1775" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tococa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tococa" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Tococa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sensu stricto have the testa cells with straight walls (
<bibRefCitation author="Michelangeli, FA" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" pagination="211 - 234" publicationUrl="10.2307/2666640" refId="B25" refString="Michelangeli, FA, 2000. A cladistic analysis of the genus Tococa (Melastomataceae) based on morphological data. Systematic Botany 25: 211 - 234, DOI: 10.2307/2666640" title="A cladistic analysis of the genus Tococa (Melastomataceae) based on morphological data." url="10.2307/2666640" volume="25" year="2000">Michelangeli 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Michelangeli, FA" journalOrPublisher="Flora Neotropica Monographs" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 114" publicationUrl="http://www.jstor.org/stable/4393950" refId="B26" refString="Michelangeli, FA, 2005. A Monograph of Tococa Aublet (Melastomataceae). Flora Neotropica Monographs 98: 1 - 114, http://www.jstor.org/stable/4393950" title="A Monograph of Tococa Aublet (Melastomataceae)." url="http://www.jstor.org/stable/4393950" volume="98" year="2005">2005</bibRefCitation>
), while the testa cells in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Miconia papillosperma" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="papillosperma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Miconia papillosperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have clearly puzzle or S-shaped walls. In summary, we think that the best placement for this new species is within 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Miconia" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Miconia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
given its terminal inflorescence with flowers with rounded petals.
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">
It should be noted that the seeds of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Miconia papillosperma" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="papillosperma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Miconia papillosperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unique within the tribe. To date the seeds of more than 500 species of the close to 2000 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="tribe" tribe="Miconieae">Miconieae</taxonomicName>
have been imaged and studied and none of them have papillose testa (
<bibRefCitation author="Groenendijk, JP" journalOrPublisher="Acta Botanica Neerlandica" pageId="6" pageNumber="37" pagination="323 - 344" publicationUrl="10.1111/j.1438-8677.1996.tb00520.x" refId="B10" refString="Groenendijk, JP, Bouman, F, Cleef, AM, 1996. An exploratory study on seed morphology of Miconia Ruiz and Pavon (Melastomataceae), with taxonomic and ecological implications. Acta Botanica Neerlandica 45: 323 - 344, DOI: 10.1111/j.1438-8677.1996.tb00520.x" title="An exploratory study on seed morphology of Miconia Ruiz and Pavon (Melastomataceae), with taxonomic and ecological implications." url="10.1111/j.1438-8677.1996.tb00520.x" volume="45" year="1996">Groenendijk et al. 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Michelangeli, FA" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" pagination="211 - 234" publicationUrl="10.2307/2666640" refId="B25" refString="Michelangeli, FA, 2000. A cladistic analysis of the genus Tococa (Melastomataceae) based on morphological data. Systematic Botany 25: 211 - 234, DOI: 10.2307/2666640" title="A cladistic analysis of the genus Tococa (Melastomataceae) based on morphological data." url="10.2307/2666640" volume="25" year="2000">Michelangeli 2000</bibRefCitation>
; Martin and Michelangeli 2008; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ocampo, G" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 129" publicationUrl="10.11646/phytotaxa.80.1.1" refId="B33" refString="Ocampo, G, Almeda, F, 2013. Seed diversity in the Miconieae (Melastomataceae): morphological characterization and phenetic relationships. Phytotaxa 80: 1 - 129, DOI: 10.11646/phytotaxa.80.1.1" title="Seed diversity in the Miconieae (Melastomataceae): morphological characterization and phenetic relationships." url="10.11646/phytotaxa.80.1.1" volume="80" year="2013">Ocampo and Almeda 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ocampo, G" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" publicationUrl="10.1371/journal.pone.0100561" refId="B34" refString="Ocampo, G, Michelangeli, FA, Almeda, F, 2014. Seed Diversity in the Tribe Miconieae (Melastomataceae): Taxonomic, Systematic, and Evolutionary Implications. PLoS ONE 9(6): e100561. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0100561" title="Seed Diversity in the Tribe Miconieae (Melastomataceae): Taxonomic, Systematic, and Evolutionary Implications. PLoS ONE 9 (6): e 100561. doi:" url="10.1371/journal.pone.0100561" year="2014">Ocampo et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
